entry.title: Fully allocate space when there is a size mutation in the custom flex rule.
entry.content:
When space is constrained for multi-line labels, the size mutates due to

character wrapping. In this case, the remaining space generated by the

mutation cannot be allocated. eg: HelpBubbleView.



Here we introduce the CSS flexbox allocation algorithm. But there are

some differences in the behavior of views. So based on the css flexbox

algorithm, some special modifications were made to adapt the current

behavior.

entry.title: Make periodic logs synchronous when shutting down
entry.content:
Full context:

Currently, we finalize periodic logs asynchronously. This includes

things like serializing the log. Once that's done, a "reply task" is

posted back on the main thread to store that finalized log in Local

State.



One possible issue is that while the background task to finalize the

log is running, the user may shut down the browser. When this happens,

the "reply task" is never run, so the finalized log is lost. For this

reason, we don't do "delta snapshots" in the background task, since

that could lead to data loss. For example, say we did "delta

snapshots" in the background, which removes the histogram samples from

the underlying storage. If the browser was shut down by the user and

the finalized log was never stored, then the samples would be lost.

Instead, in the background task, we take a snapshot of the samples

(without removing them from the underlying storage) and fill them into

the log. We only remove the samples from the underlying when we're

back on the main thread and stored the finalized log in Local State.



There is a feature to change this behaviour:

"MetricsServiceDeltaSnapshotInBg". When enabled, this performs full

"delta snapshots" in the background task (i.e. samples are removed

from the underlying storage and filled into the log). To make sure

there is no data loss, before the background task is posted, we create

a "ScopedKeepAlive", which forces the browser to stay alive (process

won't shut down). We destroy the ScopedKeepAlive after we're back on

the main thread and stored the finalized log in Local State.



However, according to crbug.com/1490916, there can be a short period

of time where we try to create a periodic ongoing log, but the browser

shutdown has already started. When this happens, creating a

ScopedKeepAlive triggers a CHECK. This CL makes it so that if shutdown

has already started, instead of creating a ScopedKeepAlive, do the

work synchronously instead.



This solution was discussed with in scheduler-dev:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/scheduler-dev/c/A1d7c-sGMmk/m/jWkM5Dh3AwAJ



And seems like a similar solution already exists in Sync:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/background_sync/background_sync_delegate_impl.cc;l=63-68;drc=142b92dd3032947a049d244cded805617ea9b994





Bug: 1464694,1490916

entry.title: Simplify encryption error predicates for signed-in non-syncing users
entry.content:
No behavior change.



Before crrev.com/c/4874142, the opt-in for passwords-account-storage

on desktop was implemented via

DataTypeController::GetPreconditionState(), rather than SyncUserSettings::GetSelectedTypes(). As a consequence, for users

who hadn't opted in, PASSWORDS was nevertheless considered

"preferred", and the following could return true:

1. SyncUserSettings::IsTrustedVaultKeyRequiredForPreferredDataTypes()

2. SyncUserSettings::IsTrustedVaultRecoverabilityDegraded()

This required special helpers:

3. ShouldShowSyncKeysMissingError()

4. ShouldShowTrustedVaultDegradedRecoverabilityError()

which checked for the opt-in on top of 1/2.



Now 1 and 2 just work, this CL removes 3 and 4.



Fixed: 1447083

entry.content:
The end goal is to have a single function for CC form filling or

preview. The fetching of the CC number should happen on the caller

side, since this task is completely independent from the BAM

area of responsibility.



Callers need to know if the form contains a CC number field. They

have unparsed FormData and FormFieldData. Since form cache is private

to the BAM, we need to introduce a dedicated function to make the

cache query.



Next steps: migrate the CC number fetching checks to the callers.

The callers are the AutofillExternalDelegate and the

TouchToFillAndroidDelegate.



This function will become obsolete once crbug.com/1331312 is fixed

and entities outside the BAM operate with the parsed FormStructure

and AutofillField.



See go/autofill-filling-api-refactoring for details.

entry.title: Make SingleFieldFormFiller::SuggestionHandler a callback
entry.content:
Currently, SingleFieldFormFiller::OnGetSingleFieldSuggestions() requires

an argument of type SuggestionHandler. This is an interface containing

a single function OnSuggestionsReturned(). Since Autocomplete

suggestions are generated async, this mechanism is necessary to return

the suggestions once they are available.



This CL replaces this Java-style interface with a more C++-style

callback. It does so by defining OnSuggestionsReturnedCallback in

SingleFieldFormFiller and changing the parameter type of

OnGetSingleFieldSuggestions().



The tests are trivially changed to use base::MockCallback<> instead,

which amounts to the majority of the delta of this CL.

entry.title: Remove SingleFieldFormFiller::CancelPendingQueries() parameter
entry.content:
SingleFieldFormFiller (the interface) requires the implementation of a

CancelPendingQueries(handler) function. handler identifies the caller of

the original OnGetSingleFieldSuggestions() call, whose queries are

supposed to get cancelled.



In practice, the only handler that's ever used is the BAM. This CL

removes the handler parameter from the function, and always makes

CancelPendingQueries() cancel all pending queries.

This reduces unneeded complexity and simplifies some tests.

More importantly, it makes it possible to migrate

SingleFieldFormFiller::SuggestionHandler to a callback. Once this is

done, the concept of "cancelling queries for a specific caller" doesn't

make sense anymore (unless we want to introduce some sort of caller ID).



In practice, since only Autocomplete suggestions are generated

asynchronously, CancelPendingQueries() only has an implementation in the

AutocompleteHistoryManager. In light of the platform developments,

it seems possible that more async SingleFieldFormFillers will be added

in the future. For this reason, the function is kept in the interface (

rather than renaming it to something more specific like

CancelPendingAutocompleteQueries()).

entry.title: Remove AutofillSubject, AutofillObserver and TestAutofillAsyncObserver
entry.content:
Unlike the name suggests, these classes are about Autocomplete.

AutofillSubject + AutofillObserver in particular are a way to observe

some events of the AutocompleteHistoryManager. TestAutofillAsyncObserver

is an additional class that is built on top of AutofillObserver to wait

for events.



All this logic is unused in production and only needed for a single

browser test. By using the TestAutofillManagerWaiter and by waiting

for tasks on the DB sequence to complete, these classes become obsolete.



AutofillSubject also happens to be a base class of the IbanManager and

the MerchantPromoCodeManager. For them, this mechanism is completely

unused and likely just exists due to blind copy-pasting from the

AutocompleteHistoryManager (they are all SingleFieldFormFillers).
